\f0\fs24 \cf0 Growing up, my kitchen was a battleground of smells. On one side, there was my dad\'92s side of the family\'97the German-American half. That meant mashed potatoes, pot roast, and maybe some sauerkraut if we were feeling adventurous. It was \'93normal\'94 food. It smelled like butter and salt. Then there was my mom\'92s side. She moved here from Malaysia when she was in her twenties, and her cooking smelled like everything at once: pungent shrimp paste, sharp ginger, and spicy sambal that made me sneeze the second I walked through the door.\
\
To be honest, for a long time, I hated it.\
\
I remember this one time in middle school when my mom packed me laksa in a thermos for lunch. When I opened it in the cafeteria, this thick, coconut-curry scent drifted out. It wasn't bad, but it was *loud*. My friend Tyler made a face and asked, \'93What is that? It smells like old fish.\'94 I felt my face get hot. I shoved the lid back on and told him it was just some weird soup my mom made. I didn't eat the rest of the day.\
\
