\
Everything changed during my sophomore year when my grandma (my Ma Ma) came to visit from Malaysia. She didn't speak much English, but she spoke through food. One afternoon, she decided to teach me how to make Hainanese chicken rice. I tried to make an excuse to go to my room, but she grabbed my wrist and handed me a head of garlic.\
\
As we worked, she showed me how the rice isn't just rice\'97it\'92s toasted in ginger and chicken fat until it glows. She told me stories (with my mom translating) about how this was the ultimate comfort food back home. When we finally sat down to eat, I didn't just taste the salt or the spice. I tasted the effort. I realized that while I was busy being embarrassed, my mom and grandma were literally pouring their history into these bowls.\
\
I started looking at my mom\'92s cooking differently after that. I realized that her "weird" ingredients weren't something to hide; they were her way of staying connected to a home she left thousands of miles away. Now, when I walk into the house and smell that sharp scent of shrimp paste, I don't cringe. I actually get hungry. \
\
